> 
> This also assumes no tipping points are passed which could potentially lead to additional emissions (e.g., permafrost thawing). And it applies to CO$_2$ specifically—not emissions of other greenhouse gases, which can have different lifetimes and warming impacts.
> 
> In addition to the warming from CO$_2$, the immediate cessation of all emissions means an immediate cessation of aerosol emissions. Because aerosols can have a cooling influence, a sudden stop in their production could lead to a temporary, rapid increase in temperature.
> 
> In conclusion, even if we stop all CO$_2$ emissions today, it could take many centuries or millennia before temperatures return to pre-industrial levels. As such, solutions to climate change require a combination of emissions reductions, carbon capture, and potentially, geoengineering to actively cool the Earth. However, each of these strategies has its own challenges and risks.
